<br>
The reason mages (and necros) have a bad rap is poor pet control.  If you know when not to summon a pet.  And when you do summon a pet, if you know how to control it, then there shouldn't be any problems.  Mages can provide utility (during long camps you run out of food or bandages), using CoH to pull someone out of a bad situation or to get into a tough camp spot, and most importantly providing 2 group members for the price of one.<br>
<br>
Here's an illustration of what gives mages a bad rep.<br>
1) I'm in a dungeon with some friends and a mage guildie wants to join us.  I go up to bring him down to join everyone and I didn't notice that his first action was to summon a pet to escort him.  This is a pretty tight and winding dungeon.  His pet aggros several mobs on the way down getting him killed, and putting me and the group in danger.  He should have waited until we reached the group to decide whether or not to summon the pet but he said it was a reflex.<br>
2) I'm in a different dungeon with a different mage.  We just finished a tough fight, heals are in progress and people are medding.  Suddenly the mage says, &quot;hey, has anyone seen my pet?&quot;  A feeling of impending horror descends upon us.  The pet dies somewhere and the mobs come tracking down the mage, resulting in a total wipeout of the group.<br>
3) We're in a tough dungeon, and we have a chanter for mezzing.  We tell the mage, it probably wouldn't be a good idea to summon a pet, but he insists that he has great control.  After several mez breaks by the pet, the chanter eventually gets killed, and he leaves the group in disgust.<br>
<br>
If you can avoid examples like the ones listed above, then you would fit into groups well.  The problem is, the above examples happen more often than not.  And while there are stupid people playing all classes, most non-solo classes are forced into learning grouping tactics very early on, while mages and necros (and druids also) have the option to spend lots of time soloing and they do.<br>
<br>
Now here are some good examples:<br>
1) We're outdoors hunting giants.  The mage in our group tells me about a new strategy he learned.  I run out and pull a giant back to the group.  When I get back I try to position the giant so it stops on top of the pet who immediately aggros and tanks.  Even though I'm a warrior, we're saving the druid (we didn't have a cleric at the time) mana from healing me.  A very fast and efficient pulling process developed from that.<br>
2) We're in a tough dungeon and a train is incoming.  The mage sends the pet into the fray, giving the wizard enough time to evac us before we get swarmed.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry that mages (and necros) have developed a bad rep for grouping.  I hope some day that more group oriented pet casters start changing that perception.  For now, if I have a spot open, I'm not going to discriminate.<br>
<br>
